2 HOUSE BILL 701
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2013 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 Preamble
4 WHEREAS, Vernal pools are unique, small–scale ecosystems that contribute
5 significantly to the biodiversity of Maryland by providing habitat for species that cannot
6 reproduce in alternative habitats, including the wood frog, mole salamanders, and fairy
7 shrimp; and
8 WHEREAS, Vernal pools provide a significant amount of ecosystem services as they
9 occur frequently throughout Maryland and have the capacity to replenish groundwater and
10 filter stormwater flows; and
11 WHEREAS, Nontidal wetlands that meet the three federal wetland delineation
12 criteria of hydrology, hydric soils, and hydrophytic vegetation, including vernal pools that
13 satisfy those criteria, are regulated and protected by the State; and
14 WHEREAS, Vernal pools that do not meet all three federal wetland delineation
15 criteria are not afforded the regulatory protections applicable to nontidal wetlands in the
16 State and may suffer impairments or losses without regulatory review or approval; now,
17 therefore,
18 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
19 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
20 Article – Environment
21 5–205.
22 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
23 INDICATED.
24 (2) “AGRICULTURAL ACTIVITY” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
25 5–901 OF THIS TITLE.
26 (3) “FORESTRY ACTIVITY” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 5–901 OF
27 THIS TITLE.
28 (4) “NONTIDAL WETLAND” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 5–901 OF
29 THIS TITLE.
30 (5) “OBLIGATE SPECIES” MEANS AN ANIMAL SPECIES THAT DEPENDS
31 ON VERNAL POOLS AS A NECESSARY PART OF ITS LIFE CYCLE.

HOUSE BILL 701 3
1 (6) “QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL” MEANS A CONFINED DEPRESSION
2 THAT:
3 (I) HAS SURFACE WATER FOR PART OF THE YEAR;
4 (II) PROVIDES A PERSISTENT OR BREEDING HABITAT FOR
5 OBLIGATE SPECIES, INCLUDING NATIVE AMPHIBIANS AND INVERTEBRATES; AND
6 (III) DOES NOT MEET THE CRITERIA FOR PROTECTION AS A
7 NONTIDAL WETLAND UNDER FEDERAL OR STATE LAW, INCLUDING THE FEDERAL
8 WETLAND DELINEATION CRITERIA OF HYDROLOGY, HYDRIC SOILS, AND
9 HYDROPHYTIC VEGETATION.
10 (7) (I) “REGULATED ACTIVITY” MEANS ANY OF THE FOLLOWING
11 ACTIVITIES IN A QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL OR WITHIN A BUFFER AROUND A
12 QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL:
13 1. THE REMOVAL, EXCAVATION, OR DREDGING OF SOIL,
14 SAND, GRAVEL, MINERALS, ORGANIC MATTER, OR MATERIALS OF ANY KIND;
15 2. THE CHANGING OF EXISTING DRAINAGE
16 CHARACTERISTICS, SEDIMENTATION PATTERNS, FLOW PATTERNS, OR FLOOD
17 RETENTION CHARACTERISTICS;
18 3. THE DISTURBANCE OF THE WATER LEVEL OR WATER
19 TABLE BY DRAINAGE, IMPOUNDMENT, OR OTHER MEANS;
20 4. THE DUMPING, DISCHARGING OF MATERIAL, OR
21 FILLING WITH MATERIAL, INCLUDING THE DRIVING OF PILES AND PLACING OF
22 OBSTRUCTIONS;
23 5. THE GRADING OR REMOVAL OF MATERIAL THAT
24 WOULD ALTER EXISTING TOPOGRAPHY; AND
25 6. THE DESTRUCTION OR REMOVAL OF PLANT LIFE
26 THAT WOULD ALTER THE CHARACTER OF A QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL.
27 (II) “REGULATED ACTIVITY” DOES NOT INCLUDE AN
28 AGRICULTURAL ACTIVITY OR FORESTRY ACTIVITY AS DEFINED IN THIS SECTION.
29 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO:

4 HOUSE BILL 701
1 (1) ESTABLISH AND MAINTAIN A LIST OF QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS
2 IN THE STATE;
3 (2) ESTABLISH PROTECTIONS RELATED TO THE PRESERVATION OF
4 QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS IN THE STATE;
5 (3) ESTABLISH PROTECTIONS FOR BUFFERS AROUND QUALIFIED
6 VERNAL POOLS IN THE STATE; AND
7 (4) REQUIRE THAT A PERSON CONDUCTING A REGULATED ACTIVITY
8 RESULTING IN IMPAIRMENTS OR LOSSES TO A QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL OR A
9 BUFFER AROUND A QUALIFIED VERNAL POOL:
10 (I) AVOID IMPAIRMENTS AND LOSSES TO THE MAXIMUM
11 EXTENT PRACTICABLE;
12 (II) MINIMIZE IMPAIRMENTS AND LOSSES TO THE MAXIMUM
13 EXTENT PRACTICABLE WHERE AVOIDANCE IS NOT POSSIBLE; AND
14 (III) PROVIDE COMPENSATION OR OTHER MITIGATION AS
15 DETERMINED BY THE DEPARTMENT FOR ANY REMAINING UNAVOIDABLE
16 IMPAIRMENTS AND LOSSES.
17 (C) THE REGULATIONS ADOPTED UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION
18 SHALL APPLY ONLY TO QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS THAT HAVE BEEN IDENTIFIED OR
19 DOCUMENTED BY:
20 (1) THE DEPARTMENT;
21 (2) A PERSON USING IDENTIFICATION METHODS APPROVED BY THE
22 DEPARTMENT, INCLUDING MAPPING OR OTHER SCIENTIFIC INFORMATION; OR
23 (3) A CERTIFIED WETLAND DELINEATOR DURING A SITE ASSESSMENT
24 CONDUCTED BEFORE THE ISSUANCE OF A PERMIT FOR A REGULATED ACTIVITY.
25 (D) (1) IN DEVELOPING THE REGULATIONS UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF
26 THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL, TO THE EXTENT PRACTICABLE:
27 (I) ENSURE THAT THE BUFFER SPECIFICATIONS FOR
28 QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS BE CONSISTENT WITH THE BUFFER SPECIFICATIONS FOR
29 NONTIDAL WETLANDS UNDER § 5–906 OF THIS TITLE; AND

HOUSE BILL 701 5
1 (II) ENSURE THAT THE COMPENSATION AND MITIGATION
2 REQUIREMENTS FOR IMPAIRMENTS AND LOSSES WITHIN QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS
3 BE CONSISTENT WITH THE COMPENSATION AND MITIGATION REQUIREMENTS FOR
4 IMPAIRMENTS AND LOSSES WITHIN NONTIDAL WETLANDS UNDER §§ 5–909 AND
5 5–910 OF THIS TITLE.
6 (2) IN ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF
7 THIS SUBSECTION, THE DEPARTMENT MAY:
8 (I) USE MAPPING OR OTHER SCIENTIFIC INFORMATION TO
9 IDENTIFY ADDITIONAL QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS FOR INCLUSION ON THE
10 DEPARTMENT’S LIST OF QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS; AND
11 (II) CONSULT WITH ANY STAKEHOLDER GROUP AS
12 APPROPRIATE, INCLUDING THE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND THE
13 UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND.
14 (E) IN ISSUING A PERMIT FOR A REGULATED ACTIVITY, THE DEPARTMENT
15 SHALL PROVIDE PROTECTIONS FOR ANY QUALIFIED VERNAL POOLS THAT ARE:
16 (1) LISTED BY THE DEPARTMENT IN ACCORDANCE WITH
17 SUBSECTIONS (B) AND (C) OF THIS SECTION; AND
18 (2) LOCATED WITHIN THE GEOGRAPHIC AREA COVERED BY THE
19 PERMIT.
20 5–901.
21 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
22 (b) (1) “Agricultural activity” means aquaculture and farming activities.
23 (2) “Agricultural activity” includes:
24 (i) Plowing, tillage, cropping, seeding, cultivating, and harvesting
25 for the production of food and fiber products; and
26 (ii) The grazing of livestock.
27 (f) “Forestry activity” means planting, cultivating, thinning, harvesting, or any
28 other activity undertaken to use forest resources or to improve their quality or productivity.
29 (m) (1) “Nontidal wetland” means an area that is inundated or saturated by
30 surface water or groundwater at a frequency and duration sufficient to support, and that

6 HOUSE BILL 701
1 under normal circumstances does support, a prevalence of vegetation typically adapted for
2 life in saturated soil conditions, commonly known as hydrophytic vegetation.
3 (2) The determination of whether an area is a nontidal wetland shall be
4 made in accordance with the publication known as the “Federal Manual for Identifying and
5 Delineating Jurisdictional Wetlands”, published in 1989 and as may be amended.
6 (3) “Nontidal wetlands” do not include tidal wetlands regulated under Title
7 16 of this article.
8 Article – Natural Resources
9 1–1002.
10 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
11 INDICATED.
12 (2) “FACULTATIVE SPECIES” MEANS AN ANIMAL SPECIES THAT USES
13 VERNAL POOLS IRREGULARLY.
14 (3) “OBLIGATE SPECIES” MEANS AN ANIMAL SPECIES THAT DEPENDS
15 ON VERNAL POOLS AS A NECESSARY PART OF ITS LIFE CYCLE.
16 (4) “TYPICAL YEAR” MEANS A YEAR IN WHICH RAINFALL TOTALS
17 MEET OR EXCEED THE AVERAGE YEARLY RAINFALL FROM THE PREVIOUS 30 YEARS
18 FOR THE LOCATION WITHIN WHICH THE VERNAL POOL IS LOCATED.
19 (5) “VERNAL POOL” MEANS A CONFINED DEPRESSION THAT:
20 (I) HAS SURFACE WATER FOR AT LEAST 2 CONSECUTIVE
21 MONTHS BETWEEN NOVEMBER AND MAY IN A TYPICAL YEAR;
22 (II) EXPERIENCES A DECREASE IN WATER LEVEL TO 6 INCHES
23 OR LESS BETWEEN JUNE AND SEPTEMBER IN A TYPICAL YEAR;
24 (III) PROVIDES A PERSISTENT OR BREEDING HABITAT FOR
25 VARIOUS ANIMAL SPECIES, INCLUDING NATIVE AMPHIBIANS AND INVERTEBRATES
26 THAT ARE FACULTATIVE SPECIES OR OBLIGATE SPECIES;
27 (IV) CONTAINS LESS THAN 30% AERIAL COVER OF EMERGENT
28 VEGETATION WHEN FULL;
29 (V) IS PREDOMINANTLY OR PARTIALLY SHADED BY WOODY
30 VEGETATION;

HOUSE BILL 701 7
1 (VI) IS LESS THAN 5 ACRES IN SIZE; AND
2 (VII) MAY HAVE INTERMITTENT, TEMPORARY CONNECTIONS TO
3 OTHER BODIES OF WATER.
4 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
5 (1) IN COORDINATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
6 ENVIRONMENT, CREATE AND MAINTAIN A LIST OF VERNAL POOLS IN THE STATE;
7 (2) ESTABLISH CRITERIA AND PROCEDURES FOR IDENTIFYING AND
8 INCLUDING VERNAL POOLS ON THE LIST, INCLUDING:
9 (I) VERNAL POOLS IDENTIFIED BY THE DEPARTMENT IN
10 CARRYING OUT ITS DUTIES SET FORTH IN THIS ARTICLE;
11 (II) LOCATIONS THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES MEET THE
12 DEFINITION OF A VERNAL POOL UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION; AND
13 (III) VERNAL POOLS IDENTIFIED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
14 ENVIRONMENT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION;
15 (3) AUTHORIZE:
16 (I) USING MAPPING OR OTHER SCIENTIFIC INFORMATION TO
17 IDENTIFY ADDITIONAL VERNAL POOLS FOR INCLUSION ON THE LIST; AND
18 (II) CONSULTING WITH ANY STAKEHOLDER GROUP AS
19 APPROPRIATE, INCLUDING THE DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE
20 UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND, TO IDENTIFY VERNAL POOLS FOR INCLUSION ON THE
21 LIST; AND
22 (4) PROVIDE FOR PUBLICATION OF THE LIST OF VERNAL POOLS ON
23 THE DEPARTMENT’S WEBSITE.
24 (C) (1) THE DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT SHALL DESIGNATE
25 STAFF TO RECEIVE TRAINING IN VERNAL POOL IDENTIFICATION.
26 (2) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE VERNAL POOL
27 IDENTIFICATION TRAINING TO THE STAFF DESIGNATED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF
28 THIS SUBSECTION.
29 (3) IF, IN CARRYING OUT RESPONSIBILITIES UNDER TITLE 5,
30 SUBTITLE 9 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE, STAFF TRAINED UNDER THIS

8 HOUSE BILL 701
1 SUBSECTION IDENTIFY A LOCATION THAT MAY QUALIFY AS A VERNAL POOL, THE
2 DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT SHALL NOTIFY THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
3 LOCATION FOR POSSIBLE INCLUSION ON THE LIST ESTABLISHED UNDER
4 SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION.
5 (4) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION SHALL BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT THE
6 AUTHORITY OF THE DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT TO REGULATE VERNAL
7 POOLS THAT MEET THE DEFINITION OF NONTIDAL WETLANDS UNDER TITLE 5,
8 SUBTITLE 9 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE.
9 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
10 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
